# Gleason mod-8 (V17 §XVII obligation)

Gleason's theorem (1971): every doubly-even self-dual binary linear code has
length divisible by 8.

This is the SZL governance analog of the "8-receipt closure invariant" claim
in v17 §XVII — that codes admissible under SZL gate-receipt discipline must
have length 8·m for some m ∈ ℕ.

## Mathematical content

A binary linear code C of length n is doubly-even if every codeword has
Hamming weight ≡ 0 (mod 4), and self-dual if C = C⊥ under the standard
mod-2 inner product. Gleason's 1971 proof uses the MacWilliams identity to
show that the weight enumerator W_C(x,y) must be invariant under both the
substitution (x,y) ↦ ((x+y)/√2, (x-y)/√2) (MacWilliams identity for
self-dual codes) and (x,y) ↦ (x, iy) (doubly-even condition). These two
invariances generate a finite group G of order 192 whose ring of invariants is
generated by g₈ = x⁸ + 14x⁴y⁴ + y⁸ (degree 8) and a degree-24 element —
hence the minimum possible non-trivial degree forces n ≡ 0 (mod 8).

## Citations

  - Gleason, A. M. (1971). "Weight polynomials of self-dual codes and the
